stylometry: The variables you must consider when setting the safety stock is demand, along with the different costs associated with holding extra inventory in your warehouse, and lead time with products (how fast they get to your company after you order them).  How high are the holding costs.  If the holding costs are extremly high but the ordering cost is low and the lead time is only 2 days it would not make sense to keep a very large amount of safety stock in your warehouse.  Now if the ordering costs are extremely high and it takes two weeks to receive the products you ordered, then it would make more sense to keep more safety stock than the example described before this one.  THe goal is to balance the different variables to come up with the most effective and cost efficient way of handling inventory and your safety stock.  In the middle of the hardware company probably isnt going to keep a safety stock of snow shovels because there is no demand for shovels this time of year.
